{"source_key":"sha256-f88bd5c54ac5fbbfc982c6d403b2565f","record_index":297,"record_hash":"sha256:71f7d2b8d59c18b3cfc2850b9ddd03ad8a88460dabf4f2543c61d5e94c88a2da","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:35:11.919Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: c48047\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 748\nOutput:\n\nIf the metadata ref is missing or cannot be fetched, the page should show a\nclear empty state rather than treating the PR as having no agent work:\n\n```text\nNo Agent Trail metadata was found for this public pull request.\n```\n\nThat distinction matters because \"not fetchable\" and \"no captured sessions\"\nmean different things.\n\n## Relationship Model\n\nOne pull request may relate to many sessions. One session may relate to many\npull requests or branches.\n\nThe durable object remains the project-scoped session. Pull requests, reviews,\nbranches, and changes should reference session or turn keys; they should not own\ncopies of transcript records.\n\nThe first Agent Trail implementation can start from:\n\n1. pull request number as a `review` target, such as\n   `gitbutler-review:13936`\n2. PR head branch as a branch target, if GitHub metadata is available\n3. related change identifiers, if available later\n4. `but-agentlog` related-session lookup across the candidate targets\n4. verified related turns from stored observed targets\n5. bounded transcript hydration for selected turns\n\n## Review Experience\n\nThe default view should be compact and review-focused.\n\nShow:\n\n- what the human asked the agent to do\n- what the agent said it changed\n- what commands or tools it ran\n- what validation passed or failed\n- important decisions and tradeoffs\n- warnings where the trail is weak or incomplete\n\nDo not default to dumping every message or every tool result. Exact records\nshould be available through drill-down.\n\nUseful sections:\n\n- Overview\n- Timeline\n- Prompts\n- Claims\n- Validation\n- Open Questions\n- Raw Records\n\n`Raw Records` should be secondary. It exists for evidence and debugging, not as\nthe main review page.\n\n## Session Browsing Experience\n\nThe Agent Trail webpage should let a reviewer browse the related agent sessions\nin a user-friendly way.\n\nThe browsing experience should not feel like opening a raw JSON log or a giant\nchat transcript. It should feel like exploring the working history behind the\npull request.\n\nGood session browsing behavior:\n\n- show related sessions as a small list with readable labels, agent/provider,\n  capture time, and relevance reason\n- show turns within a selected session as a compact timeline\n- group records into human request, assistant response, tool call, tool result,\n  and validation blocks\n- collapse noisy tool output by default\n- highlight commands that changed files, ran tests, failed, or produced useful\n  evidence\n- make related branches, reviews, changes, files, and validation attempts easy\n  to scan\n- let the user expand exact transcript records when they need evidence\n- preserve chronological order without forcing the user to read every record\n\nThe reviewer should be able to answer:\n\n- what did the human ask?\n- what did the agent claim it did?\n- what files or areas did it touch or inspect?\n- what commands/tools ran?\n- what validation passed, failed, or was skipped?\n- what decisions, doubts, or follow-ups appeared during the work?\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:35:11.919Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}